Maryland state police performance dashboard ~ Quarterly Data

This analysis explores the relationship between three variables - Medevac Missions, Cross Border Criminal Investigations, and Impaired Driving Arrests - and their seasonal patterns. The main research question is: Are there significant differences in these variables across seasons, and do the seasons affect Total Traffic Stops? Two hypotheses guide this investigation:

  1. There is a distinct difference in Medevac Missions, Cross Border Criminal Investigations, and Impaired Driving Arrests.

  2. The colder seasons (Q1 & Q4) will produce more Impaired Driving Arrests than Q2 and Q3.

The data from the MSP Performance Dashboard shows that Total Traffic Stops vary by quarter. In warmer seasons, such as spring and summer, there tends to be an increase in these stops. Perhaps the combination of holiday celebrations, warm weather, and more people attending social events contributes to this trend. Conversely, during colder months, the number of Total Traffic Stops may decrease. This seasonal fluctuation is worth exploring further1.

Using a scatter plot with a trend line shows the relationship between Total Traffic Stops and Time Period, revealing a pattern across the given time span. The trend line identifies average changes (slope) and peaks reflecting the most significant shifts.

library(ggplot2)

# Load the data
MSP <- read.csv("~/Maryland_State_Police_Performance_Dashboard_-_Quarterly_Data_20240418.csv")

# Using a Year column to order the data chronologically
MSP$TimePeriod <- paste(MSP$Year, MSP$Quarter)

# Converting TimePeriod to a format that can be ordered correctly in the plot
MSP$TimePeriod <- factor(MSP$TimePeriod, levels = unique(MSP$TimePeriod))

# Color palette for quarters
colors <- c("Q1" = "salmon", "Q2" = "cornflowerblue", "Q3" = "khaki", "Q4" = "olivedrab")

# Scatter plot with color-coded points and a line of best fit
ggplot(MSP, aes(x = TimePeriod, y = Total.Traffic.Stops)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = Quarter), size = 3) +  # Color-coded points
  scale_color_manual(values = colors) +  # Set colors for each quarter
  geom_line(group = 1, colour = "gray40") +  # Connects all points with a gray line
  geom_smooth(aes(group = 1), method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "black") +  # Adds a line of best fit across all quarters
  labs(title = "Total Traffic Stops Over Time",
       x = "Time Period",
       y = "Total Traffic Stops",
       color = "Quarter") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))  # Rotate x labels for better visibility
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

There is a clear decline in traffic stops overall, which could be attributed to factors such as COVID-19. Notably, there is a consistent uptick in stops during warmer months, particularly in Q2 and Q3. Peaks in Q3 during specific years (2014, 2015, 2017, and 2019) are also evident.

To substantiate these observations, I aimed to calculate the means and standard deviations for each quarter and rank them accordingly.

library(dplyr)

# Load the data
MSP <- read.csv("~/Maryland_State_Police_Performance_Dashboard_-_Quarterly_Data_20240418.csv")

# Extract 'Quarter' and 'Year' from 'Quarter.and.Year'
MSP <- MSP %>%
  mutate(
    Quarter = substr(Quarter.and.Year, 1, 2),
    Year = substr(Quarter.and.Year, 5, 8)
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(Quarter) & !is.na(Year))

# Ensure that 'Year' and 'Quarter' are treated correctly
MSP$Year <- as.numeric(MSP$Year)
MSP$Quarter <- as.factor(MSP$Quarter)

# Remove rows with NA or missing values in Total_Traffic_Stops or Year
MSP <- na.omit(MSP)

# Calculate means and standard deviations for each quarter
quarter_stats <- MSP %>%
  group_by(Quarter) %>%
  summarise(
    Mean = mean(Total.Traffic.Stops),
    SD = sd(Total.Traffic.Stops)
  ) %>%
  arrange(desc(Mean))  # Arrange by descending mean

# Rank quarters
quarter_stats$Rank <- rank(-quarter_stats$Mean)

# Display the results
print(quarter_stats)

Now that weve identified seasonal spikes in traffic stops, its worth investigating whether theres a correlation with Impaired Driving Arrests specifically, compared to other types of traffic stops.

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

# Load the data
MSP <- read.csv("~/Maryland_State_Police_Performance_Dashboard_-_Quarterly_Data_20240418.csv")

# Ensure that 'Quarter' is a factor (if it's not already)
MSP$Quarter <- as.factor(MSP$Quarter)

# Aggregate data by quarter
MSP_agg <- MSP %>%
  group_by(Year, Quarter) %>%
  summarize(Impaired_Driving_Arrests = sum(Impaired.Driving.Arrests),
            Medevac_Missions = sum(Medevac.Missions),
            Cross_Border_Criminal_Investigations = sum(Cross.Border.Criminal.Investigations))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Year'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
# Create a column for TimePeriod
MSP_agg$TimePeriod <- paste(MSP_agg$Year, MSP_agg$Quarter)

# Plotting the graph 
ggplot(MSP_agg, aes(x = TimePeriod)) +
  geom_line(aes(y = Impaired_Driving_Arrests, color = "Impaired Driving Arrests", group = 1), stat = "identity") +
  geom_line(aes(y = Medevac_Missions, color = "Medevac Missions", group = 1), stat = "identity") +
  geom_line(aes(y = Cross_Border_Criminal_Investigations, color = "Cross-Border Criminal Investigations", group = 1), stat = "identity") +
  scale_color_manual(name = "Type", values = c("Impaired Driving Arrests" = "red", "Medevac Missions" = "blue", "Cross-Border Criminal Investigations" = "green")) +
  labs(title = "Comparison of Impaired Driving Arrests, Medevac Missions, and
       Cross-Border Criminal Investigations Over Time",
       x = "Time Period",
       y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 10, vjust = 0.5, size = 8)) # Adjust size as needed

As represented by the chart above, there were more traffic stops for impaired driving during the third quarter than any other quarter. Across only nine full years and the first quarter of 2024 Impaired Driving is cyclically repeating with the exception of 2020. Every peak of the third quarter is consistently higher for impaired driving compared to the other times of the year for all ten years. Additionally, Medevac Missions have similar patterns with in volume signifying a seasonal effect that may otherwise be overlooked.

We next use analysis of variation (ANOVA) to compare the data from all four quarters to compare the averages because it allows us to compare the means of multiple groups simultaneously. This is particularly useful in this case, as we want to examine the differences between the four quarters.

ANOVA considers the variability within each group, providing a more robust comparison of the means. This is important because it helps us identify significant differences between the quarters rather than just chance variations. ANOVA also considers the sample size of each group. It also provides a p-value, indicating the statistically significant difference between the groups. If the p-value is below a certain significant level (0.05), we reject the hypothesis and conclude there are no significant differences between the quarters. Using an ANOVA, we can statistically compare the averages of the four quarters and determine whether there are any significant differences, providing a more comprehensive understanding of the data.

# Load the data
MSP <- read.csv("~/Maryland_State_Police_Performance_Dashboard_-_Quarterly_Data_20240418.csv")

# Extract 'Quarter' and 'Year' from 'Quarter.and.Year'
MSP <- MSP %>%
  mutate(
    Quarter = substr(Quarter.and.Year, 1, 2),
    Year = substr(Quarter.and.Year, 5, 8)
  ) %>%
  filter(!is.na(Quarter) & !is.na(Year))

# Ensure that 'Year' and 'Quarter' are treated correctly
MSP$Year <- as.numeric(MSP$Year)
MSP$Quarter <- as.factor(MSP$Quarter)

# Rename Total_Traffic_Stops to match actual column name
names(MSP)[names(MSP) == "Total_Traffic_Stops"] <- "Total_Traffic_Stops"

# Remove rows with NA or missing values in Total_Traffic_Stops or Year
MSP <- na.omit(MSP)

# Perform ANOVA
anova_result <- aov(Total.Traffic.Stops ~ Quarter, data = MSP)

# Print ANOVA table
print(summary(anova_result))
##             Df    Sum Sq   Mean Sq F value Pr(>F)
## Quarter      3 1.525e+09 508464004   1.331  0.279
## Residuals   37 1.413e+10 381894276

While the ANOVA analysis did not detect a significant difference in the mean number of traffic stops between quarters (p = 0.279), the visual representations and additional calculations reveal a more nuanced story. The bar chart and trend lines suggest a consistent peak in traffic stops during the third quarter (Q3) over the ten years, indicating a seasonal pattern. Furthermore, calculating means and standard deviations for each quarter confirms that Q3 has the highest mean and is ranked first.

These findings suggest that while the overall difference between quarters may not be statistically significant, a trend within the data warrants further exploration. The high variation within each quarter, as indicated by the residual mean Sq value and the small F value, may be masking the underlying seasonal trend. The comprehensive analysis, despite the limited ability to detect differences between quarters, clearly reveals the seasonal trend in Q3 as represented by the visual charts.

Therefore, the third quarters tendency to have the highest average of Impaired Driving Arrests is likely due to seasonal factors such as summer holidays and events that contribute to increased social gatherings and alcohol consumption. Visual representations and additional calculations strongly support this conclusion, emphasizing the crucial role of combining multiple analytical approaches to uncover a deeper understanding of the data.
